---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<Layout
  title="The Experiment"
  description="How the CAL DMRadio experiment works: solenoidal LC resonator, SQUID amplifiers, and quantum-limited axion searches."
>

  <!-- Page header -->
  <section class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">CAL-Pathfinder</span>
      <h1>The Experiment</h1>
      <p class="desc">
        [One-sentence summary of the CAL experiment for the page header]
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Overview -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="two-col-60">
        <div>
          <span class="section-label">Overview</span>
          <h2 style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">How Lumped-Element Detection Works</h2>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            In a conventional microwave cavity haloscope, the detector volume must be comparable to
            the photon wavelength at the target axion frequency, which confines cavity-based searches
            to axion masses above roughly 1&nbsp;&mu;eV. In the <em>lumped-element regime</em>&mdash;
            applicable when the target wavelength far exceeds the detector size&mdash;the axion-induced
            electromagnetic signal can instead be treated as a spatially uniform effective current
            driving a simple LC circuit. The detector is characterized by its inductance and capacitance
            rather than by cavity mode structure, so pickup volume and magnet volume can be scaled
            independently of the target frequency. This opens the sub-&mu;eV mass window that cavity
            haloscopes cannot reach.
          </p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            An axion traversing a strong static magnetic field acquires an effective coupling to the
            electromagnetic field, producing a faint oscillating magnetic flux in a nearby inductive
            pickup coil. When the LC resonator is tuned so that its resonant frequency matches the
            axion oscillation frequency (&omega;<sub>a</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;m<sub>a</sub>c<sup>2</sup>/&hbar;),
            the quality factor Q enhances the axion-induced signal power relative to the thermal noise
            floor. Scanning the resonance over time&mdash;via variable capacitors or switched
            elements&mdash;allows the experiment to cover a continuous range of axion masses.
          </p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            CAL Pathfinder implements this concept using a solenoidal superconducting magnet, a coaxial
            inductive pickup surrounding the field volume, and a DC SQUID amplifier chain operating
            near 20&nbsp;mK. The SQUID provides quantum-limited noise performance essential for
            detecting the extraordinarily faint axion-induced currents at the target sensitivity. As a
            pathfinder instrument, CAL validates the lumped-element detection principle at scale,
            characterizes parasitic modes and loss mechanisms in the resonator, and develops the
            cryogenic readout hardware required for larger DMRadio-class experiments.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1rem;">
          <div class="diagram-placeholder">
            <p><strong>Detector schematic</strong></p>
            <p>Coaxial pickup coil + SQUID chain</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider">

  <!-- Setup / hardware -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label">Hardware</span>
      <h2 style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;">Detector Setup</h2>
      <div class="grid-3">
        <div class="card">
          <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;color:var(--blue);">Coaxial Resonator</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.9rem;">
            [Description of the pickup coil geometry and the LC circuit]
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;color:var(--blue);">SQUID Amplifiers</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.9rem;">
            [Description of the SQUID amplifier chain and how it achieves quantum-limited noise]
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;color:var(--blue);">Cryogenic System</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.9rem;">
            [Description of the dilution refrigerator and operating temperature]
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;color:var(--blue);">Magnet</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.9rem;">
            [Description of the superconducting magnet: field strength and how it drives axion-photon conversion]
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;color:var(--blue);">Data Acquisition</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.9rem;">
            [Description of the data acquisition chain and how axion signals are identified above the noise floor]
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;color:var(--blue);">Analysis Pipeline</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.9rem;">
            [Description of the analysis pipeline for identifying candidates and setting exclusion limits]
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="section-sm" style="background:var(--gray-50);border-top:1px solid var(--gray-200);">
    <div class="container" style="text-align:center;">
      <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Want to learn more?</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;max-width:500px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;">
        [Short invitation for visitors to read publications or get in touch]
      </p>
      <div style="display:flex;gap:1rem;justify-content:center;flex-wrap:wrap;">
        <a href={`${base}/publications/`} class="btn btn-primary">Publications</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
